To give both students and employees a break following the four-day PAASCU revisit completion, the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) suspends classes and office duty tomorrow, September 30, and will resume on October 2.

However, the deans of the School of Law and Graduate School are given the discretion to hold classes or not.

Please be guided.

text:
#OnTheGo

Jaguars take lead against Cobras, 56-46

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars dominated against the Southwestern University (SWU) PHINMA Cobras, 56-46, fending off the victory during their basketball match in Cesafi 23 at Cebu Coliseum yesterday, September 28.

From the opening tip-off, the Jaguars clearly had a game plan geared toward bagging the victory against the Cobras.

Their offense flowed seamlessly, with precise passes, sharp shoots, and a tenacious presence in the paint, which left the Cobras behind with an 8-point lead in the first quarter, 20-12.

Jaguars’ big man, Evan Jose Ejay Agbong, was in a league of his own, contributing game-high points and displaying an ability to control the tempo of the game.

Agbong shared his eagerness and preparation to win the competition.

“Hungrier pa [ako] kasi hindi naman ito ang pinaghahandaan ko na game eh, part lang ito sa process namin, pero ang pinaghahandaan namin is ang goal namin [to go] to the finals. Ang dami pang teams na haharapin namin at madami pang challenges na haharapin namin,” he explained.

As the game progressed, the Jaguars were not content with their initial lead and continued to execute fast breaks with precision and make paints that swamped their opponents, garnering a 21-point lead against the Cobras, by the end of the first half, 51-30.

Despite the Cobras’ efforts to mount a comeback in the fourth quarter, they were unable to overcome the Jaguars’ relentless onslaught, leaving a final score of 56-46.

Jaguars head coach Melo Banua, shared his sentiments about improving the team’s loophole.

“Mao gihapon ang amoang problema last game nga every time last four or three minutes, [mag]-collapse [ang offense and defense sa] mga bata, so kinahanglan pa jud nga i-build ang chemistry para sure nga modaog sa game," he shared.

The USJ-R Jaguars will face off against the Cebu Roosevelt Memorial Colleges (CRMC) Mustangs on Sunday, October 1, at 5 p.m.

via Khabzeel Clark Payao | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Photos Courtesy: Krista Marie Yaoyao | FORWARD Probationary Photographer

text:
[LITERARY]

Our Enchanting Tale
by Kady De Arca | Josenian Contributor

In the abandoned corridors of my heart,
Your footsteps suddenly echo from within.
The massive walls I built were torn apart,
Showing an open door where roses bloomed, and so, it begins.

In the night filled with a sea of stars,
You were once the moon I couldn't ever reach.
The moon I could only admire and gaze from afar,
The moon I so badly love and desire.

Then the season of autumn arrived,
Just like the leaves, I was slowly falling.
Yet the breeze of your words blew me astray,
Along with your actions, which completely lost my way.

Winter came, and your footsteps slowly faded away,
Coldness replaced the warmth within my heart.
By surprise, you finally entered my doors inserting the key,
Thus an enchanting tale began; a tale that started with pure glee.

The first road in our story,
Was the first lesson of compromise and adaptability.
Then the truth of our love came to light,
Memorable it was, truth be told, the prank you pulled gave me quite a fright.

As months passed by,
The first grenade and proceeding bullets came.
It was hard and painful, not gonna lie,
Yet every tear that dropped was worth it, because we still fought and won every battle we faced.

Now we’ve reached the here and now,
But still the war is not yet done.
Though my heart is filled with more warmth than sorrow,
For I know you're with me in every battle, we'll win.

With that, I'll confess,
In the entirety of my heart, mind, body and soul,
Your voice is my guide, your laugh is my melody,
Your eyes are my dream, the beat of your heart is my harmony.

Your arms are my home,
Your scent is my remedy.
For that my roses are yours,
And yours it shall be for all of eternity.

Illustration by Karina Adel Vestil | FORWARD Staff Artist

text:
#OnTheGo

Josenian Debatista champs USC’s Borderlands Cup

The Josenian Debatista (JD) from the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) clinched the championship title in the University of San Carlos Junior Philippine Institute of Accountants’ (USC JPIA) Borderlands Cup held on September 23-24.

USJ-R’s ‘Alice Outside of the Borderland’ team was composed of Jelene Gabutan, a fourth-year BS in Accountancy student, and Jan Kier Rizon, a third-year BS in Management Accounting student.

Rizon and Gabutan claimed the 1st and 2nd Best Speaker awards, respectively.

Rizon expressed his sentiments on winning and representing the University.

“It was a very proud moment for me to get the name of the school out there. Most especially representing our much-loved org, the Josenian Debatista,” he said.

“Our seniors really helped us train and improve as we moved along with our training sessions. Being named as champions representing the mighty banner of my alma mater that bleeds green and gold was a surreal moment,” he added.

Meanwhile, Gabutan shared the challenging experience during the competition.

“I think the hardest part about the competition was the fact that you have all these participants from different schools who also want to win so it can get quite intimidating at first,” she said.

Meanwhile, Jet Francis Camasura, a fourth-year BS in Accountancy student, earned the 3rd Best Speaker as part of the participating team.

Further, JD’s Athena Matin-aw, a third-year BA in International Studies student, served as an invited judge at the Borderlands Cup.

Matin-aw was also awarded the title of Best Adjudicator in the tournament.

“It was a nice surprise that they accepted my application to be an invited adjudicator, as admittedly I’m more experienced in debating rather than judging. But really, the award was unexpected, and I’m very grateful to the organizers (USC JPIA Debate Society) and the Adjudication Core for letting me join the tournament,” Matin-aw said.

The Borderlands Cup hosted by USC JPIA Debate Society, is a platform for novice JPIA debaters to showcase their talents and hone their skills.

It provides a competitive arena for young debaters to engage in intellectual discourse and develop their abilities in persuasive argumentation.

The Borderlands Cup Grand Finals was held online through Discord and was broadcast live at the USC JPIA Debate Society Facebook Page.

via Maria Cristina Lamug | FORWARD Probationary Writer

text:
#OnTheGo

Jaguars emerge victorious against Warriors in Cesafi basketball

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars claimed their first victory in a close game, 60-58, against the University of San Carlos (USC) Warriors during their first basketball match in Cesafi 23 at Cebu Coliseum yesterday, September 24.

The USJ-R Jaguars trailed behind the USC Warriors with a 4-point lead in the first 2 minutes of the game but eventually caught up and maintained their domination.

In the final period, the Jaguars sustained their momentum and strategized their defense against the Warriors, earning an advantage of more than 10 points.

The tension of the game heated up as the Warriors almost secured their first win when they took the game to a tie, 58-58, in the dying seconds of the last quarter.

The Jaguars’ utmost focus to augment the lead and the Warriors’ eagerness to earn the win via a 3-point shot filled the crowd with excitement.

The team finally sealed the game with a winning 2-point shot secured by Kendrick Abarquez.

USJ-R Jaguars Head Coach Melo Banua expressed his sentiments about the game.

“Gwapo kaayo ang duwa wala [nako’y] maingon sa duwa. Nahurot na akong boses so ang good thing lang ari is wala ni-give up akong mga players,” he said.

Meanwhile, the Jaguars’ team captain Jules Langres shared that he could not explain what they were feeling at the drop of a hat.

“Nagpasalamat lang ko kay God kay gitagaan mi niya’g nindot na duwa. Amo ning gi-offer sa among coach. Composed lang mi kay gianad man mi. Di pa nako ma-explain tanan kay mixed [akong] emotion ba,” Langres stated.

The USJ-R Jaguars will face off against the Southwestern University (SWU) PHINMA Cobras on September 28 at 6:45 p.m.

via Louise Lambiquit | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Photos Courtesy: Marylit Silje Cañizar | FORWARD Probationary Photographer

text:
#OnTheGo

Aspiring lawyers complete final day of 2023 Bar Exams

The aspiring lawyers concluded their three-day journey toward legal licensure as the regionalized 2023 Bar Examinations unfolded at various venues, including one at the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Basak campus, yesterday, September 24.

Ellen Lois Badon, a Bar examinee from USJ-R, shared her sentiments now that the three-day examinations are finally over.

“I feel happy that after five years nga hinaguan karon kay nahuman na gyud akong gihulat: ang Bar Exam. Dako kaayo og tabang ang mga professors, ang mga Bar officials, and ang USJ-R sa paghatag sa amoa sa ilang support. Makita sad gyud ang support sa mga tawo nga naa diri karon,” Badon said.

Badon further shared her thoughts with regards to the traffic management system as there were no road closures implemented at the USJ-R Basak campus in Basak Pardo.

“Nalipay pod ko nga sa USJ-R na-held ang regionalized Bar Exam, pero medyo layo sad gyud siya unya traffic,” Badon said.

“Siguro akong ma-suggest sa Bar Officers kay mayta’g mohatag sila og free ride sa examinees kay lisod kaayo ang biyahe,” Badon added.

Meanwhile, Gracezyl Blanco, a Bar examinee from Cagayan De Oro, also expressed her experience of the regionalized Bar Exam being held in Cebu.

“Although dinhi man ko sa Cebu nag-eskwela before, first time nako nakasulod sa USJ-R Basak. Nindot siya and daghan og facilities pero traffic gyud siya inig pauli. Pero usually sayo man pod mi sa buntag so okay ra siya,” she said.

As aspiring lawyers, Badon and Blanco held high hopes for all examinees.

“Kung ihatag sa Ginoo na mahimo ming abogado, unta dili makalimtan ang reason ngano ni-choose mi mahimong lawyer: To bring justice to those that are in need,” Badon concluded.

Moreover, Zoilo Yu, a Basak Pardo Barangay Public Safety Officer (BPSO), conveyed his experiences while working onsite.

“Malipay mi nga respetohon mi sa among mga gibadlong kay makita namo na wala ray aberya sa pag-take sa mga examinees. Kalipay pod namo na makita ang ilang pagdasig ug ang pagkawala sa ilang kakapoy gikan sa pag-take kada naay mo-congratulate nila,” Yu said.

The Supreme Court chose two private universities in Cebu City which served as local testing centers (LTC) for the 2023 Bar Examinations, namely USJ-R and University of San Carlos (USC).

This marks the second time that USJ-R has served as a venue for the regionalized Bar Examinations.

via Krisha Faye Gascon | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Photos Courtesy: Heron Augustus Flores | FORWARD Probationary Artist

text:
#OnTheGo

USJ-R bets remain hopeful despite defeat

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) representatives remain optimistic despite their setback during the Miss Cebu Schools Athletics Foundation Incorporated (Cesafi) Season 23 held at the Cebu Coliseum yesterday, September 23.

In both the College and High School divisions, Heart Heather Burden and Kristen Dawn Delerio respectively, did not secure any awards.

Nevertheless, Burden expressed her gratitude for the opportunity to represent the University on a big stage.

“Although wala nadaog, happy gihapon ko ron knowing that gipili ko sa USJ-R to represent our school and this has been such a valuable experience now that I can learn something that can help me grow,” she stated.

Burden also shared that she advocates for climate change and had plans to further collaborate with the government and community to take action for practical solutions.

Meanwhile, Sophia Verron, a first-year USJ-R student and attendee of the Miss Cesafi coronation, shared her sentiments about the results.

“USJ-R this Cesafi may have not won but kami nga Josenians are still very proud of how they carried the school and [themselves,]” Verron said.

Here is the official list of winners of Miss Cesafi 2023:

College Division

Miss Cesafi - Leila Alexis Mah (USPF)
1st runner-up - Jannah Salazar, University of the Philippines-Cebu (UPC)
2nd runner-up - Leigh Chanelle Ong, Cebu Doctors’ University (CDU)

Special Awards (College Division)

Miss SMART Cesafi - Leigh Chanelle Ong (CDU)
Miss Photogenic - Reina Alexis Bentigue, Southwestern University (SWU) PHINMA

High School Division

Miss Cesafi - Camille Frances Maamo, Sacred Heart School Ateneo de Cebu (SHS-AdC)
1st runner-up - Bvhlgryl Chelsea Barinan (USPF)
2nd runner-up - Arabella Ynez Marundan Salgado (CDU)

Special Awards (High School Division)

Miss SMART Cesafi - Camille Frances Maamo (SHS AdC)
Miss Photogenic - Charmelle Lawi-An, University of Cebu (UC)

Last year during Cesafi 2022, USJ-R managed to clinch the 2nd place in the High School division and Miss Photogenic title in the College division.

via Aliyaah Alvez | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Photos Courtesy: Gabrielle Paradiang | FORWARD Probationary Photographer

text:
#OnTheGo

Josenian alumni hailed as Mr. & Ms. Press Freedom 2023

Cebu Daily News (CDN) Digital’s Christian Gerard Jamora and SunStar Cebu’s Jewil Anne Tabiolo, who both graduated from the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R), bagged the Mr. and Ms. Press Freedom 2023 title at the Axis Bar, NUSTAR Resort and Casino on September 21.

Tabiolo, a BA Journalism alumna batch 2022, relished the exclusivity and challenges of the event as it was her first time showcasing her beauty and intellect on stage.

“This event held immense personal significance as it allowed me to fulfill a lifelong ambition. An ambition of the young girl within me. Winning the crown felt like a journey of self-discovery in the most beautiful way possible," she said.

As the reigning Miss Press Freedom, Tabiolo pledged to connect with aspiring journalists, particularly within the USJ-R community.

”Our alma mater has consistently produced outstanding journalists working across various media outlets, and I’m proud to be part of that legacy and to become the new face of Cebu media,” she said.

”I believe it’s crucial to launch [a] public awareness campaign about the vital role of the press and challenge the misconceptions that portray journalists as societal villains. It’s never wrong to demand accountability and transparency from those in power,” she added.

Meanwhile, Jamora, a BA Communication alumnus batch 2022, had previous experience in pageantry during high school at Colegio De La Medalla Milagrosa, securing the Mr. Intramurals 2016 title.

“I never expected to be part of an event like this again considering that it’s one of the biggest events in Cebu. Because pageantry was never my forte nor a passion to begin with. Nevertheless, I still accepted the challenge because I look at Mr. and Ms. Press Freedom as a tool to represent the empowerment of the media,”he said.

Jamora expressed pride in representing his alma mater outside its walls and urged Josenians to uphold the institution’s core values.

“Uplift and empower the media as an institution that promotes responsibility in the fourth estate by informing the news and purveying the truth in the right way,” he said.

Furthermore, Jessa Ngojo, a social media specialist at CDN and a USJ-R graduate of BA Journalism, also secured the first runner-up spot.

via Sharry Cuizon | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Photos Courtesy: Niña Mae Oliverio | CDN Digital

text:
#OnTheGo

USJ-R CRCESI conducts reading assessments for children in Carbon

The University of San Jose-Recoletos Center for Recollect Community Engagement and Social Involvement (USJ-R CRCESI) held a program for children in Carbon to improve their reading comprehension, at the USJ-R Main Lobby earlier today, September 23.

CRCESI Project Facilitator for Outreach Activities, Jose Peace Fuentes, explained that “Paglaum sa mga Bata sa Carbon” is spearheaded to evaluate the children ages 4-15 years old in their ability to understand passages.

“I-evaluate ang ilang reading comprehension kay bisan [pila] pa ang ilang mga age, dili man mo matter sa comprehension,” Fuentes said.

The facilitator then categorized the children on how extensive their learning process would be through four categories: Non-reader, Developing, Intermediate, and Proficient.

Fuentes added that this process will not only instill knowledge, but would also help the children in the long run.

Meanwhile, Charlene Guiral, one of the volunteer teachers from the Elementary Department, shared that she finds this initiative ”helpful” because it recognizes the pressing need for improving literacy in the community.

”So far murag okay ra ang mga bata pero naa juy uban nga dili pa siya nagpantay like nine years old na sila pero ilahang grade level kay naa pa sa Grade 2 [or] Grade 1. I encountered one, kamao man siya mobasa pero mga one syllable to two syllables pa lang,” she added.

In addition, CRCESI also started to disseminate the children’s IDs for their next programs that will be held in the future.

via John Louise Lambiquit | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Photos Courtesy: Narvie Klaryzze Borja | FORWARD Probationary Photographer

text:
#OnTheGo

CDN Digital promotes responsible journalism in 31st Press Freedom Week

Media professionals from Cebu Daily News (CDN) Digital, along with journalism and communication students from various universities in Cebu, wrapped up the 31st Press Freedom Week with a forum on responsible journalism in the digital era at the University of the Philippines - Cebu (UPC) Arts and Sciences Hall on September 22.

The speakers at the forum were CDN Digital’s Content Creator Immae Lachica, Senior Copy Editor Brian Ochoa, and Social Media Manager Ralph Gurango.

In Lachica’s discussion titled “Social Media, Journalism, and the Space Between,” she emphasized the importance of news verification, particularly in the digital space.

“Not everything you see online is true, that is why you need to verify,” Lachica said.

Lachica also mentioned that journalistic ethics must still be applied in digital journalism.

“You have to be sensitive in dealing with the sources, in dealing with a tragedy, especially kay dili nana nimo ma-retract everything you post online,” she added.

Meanwhile, Ochoa highlighted that there is little to no difference between traditional and digital media in terms of journalism practices, but the digital space places a greater emphasis on delivering news in real-time.

“That is the name of the game in digital [journalism]—speed,” Ochoa said.

However, he added, “At the end of the day, you just have to choose accuracy,” noting that while digital journalism is fast-paced, accuracy remains vital.

Further, Gurango shared how newsrooms have changed in the digital landscape.

“The nature of the platform demands that you provide news as [accurately] and as fast as possible,” Gurango said.

Gurango then posed the challenge to future journalists to “constantly try to understand the tools that are available to us.”

“Being a great journalist still matters but evolving with the digital space also matters. In fact, knowing who your audience is, matters,” he added.

Moreover, Atty. Archill Niña Pistrano, assistant professor & coordinator of UPC’s Office of Anti-Sexual Harassment (OASH), emphasized in her opening speech how responsible communication is important in a democratic society.

“The media, your profession, enriches and empowers a democracy, especially in the digital age, when disinformation has become the order of the day. It is important for the young generation, the next generation, to therefore be empowered to be responsible communicators,” she said.

The students in attendance at the forum were from UPC, University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R), Cebu Normal University (CNU), and Cebu Technological University (CTU).

via Rey Martin Rio | FORWARD Staff Writer

Photos Courtesy: Christian Mananguite & Astrid Niña Vidal | FORWARD Staff Photographers
